Clustering tutorial, with solutions

k-means clustering

Kmeans in R is fairly simple:

mygroups<-kmeans( data, k) #where data is a matrix and k is the number of clusters you want

The output of this has several interesting things: in particular:

mygroups$cluster # - a label for each of the rows in your matrix corresponding to 
# what group it is assigned to (1-k)
mygroups$centers # a summary of the center of each group

The cancer-samples.txt file has two columns. These are gene expression data from two genes, in a large number of cancer samples (rows). The question is how many groups that are present in the data.

in this set, we have the advantage that we only have two genes, which means we can plot them vs each other in an x-y plot. We will do this to look at the resulting clusters. But, if we have more genes, the plotting like this would be difficult, as we have too many dimensions.

First, read in the file, plot gene1 vs gene2 as a scatterplot. It is pretty obvious that there are some sort of grouping(s) in this data. Use this to suggest a couple of different numbers for ‘k’.

SOLUTION

II: Hierarchical clustering

Use the same matrix as above, but calculate the distance between all rows using Euclidian distance, then do a hierarchical clustering and plot the tree. Look at the tree - what is it that we are looking at? What is on Y and X, what are the leaves?

Functions to look up: dist(), hclust()

If you have time: Say that we want three or four groups based on the tree. The cutree() function outputs group membership for all rows, much like the clusters in k means. You can also use the rect.hclust() function to draw rectangles on the tree, corresponing to groups. Use the cutree() function for this. Are these the same groups as corresponding k-means clustering? Hint: table().

SOLUTION

Plotting the tree using base R, then selecting k=4 and plotting those:

my.dist<-dist(cancer.data.m)
my.tree<-hclust(my.dist)
plot(my.tree)
split.tree<-cutree(my.tree, k=4)
split.tree
##  [1] 1 2 2 1 1 3 1 1 1 2 1 4 2 1 1 1 2 3 2 2 2 2 1 2 3 3 2 1 1 4 1 1 1 1 1
## [36] 4 1 1 2 1 1 3 1 1 4 1 2 1 1 2 4 1 1 2 3 2 1 1 1 1 2 2 4 2 1 2 2 1 3 4
## [71] 1 2 2 1 3 4 3 1 2 2 4 4 2 1 1 1 2 3 2 1 2 1 1 2
rect.hclust(my.tree, k=4, border="red")

–

Are those the same groups as from k-means where =4? there are more fancy ways of doing this, but I simply tabulated them with table(). This is better than a direct comparison of eg cluster 1 to cluster 1 from both groups, becasue they might find the same group but name them differently.

my.tibble<-tibble(km=my.groups$cluster, 
                  hierarch=split.tree) 
# not strictly  necessary to make a tibble, but feels cleaner. 
table(my.tibble)
##    hierarch
## km   1  2  3  4
##   1  0 30  0  0
##   2  0  0 10 10
##   3 34  0  0  0
##   4 10  0  0  0

What we can see here is that in my case, the clusters almost correspond to one another. The largest cluster, kmeans cluster 2 and hierarchical cluster 1, disagree on 6 points.

III Heatmaps

Let us first make a very simple heatmap based on the cancer data above. This will not utilize the full power of heatmaps since we only have two genes. Install the ‘pheatmap’ package and try this:

library(pheatmap)
## Warning: package 'pheatmap' was built under R version 3.5.2
#base heatap
pheatmap(cancer.data.m)

# base heatnap with different color scales
pheatmap(cancer.data.m,  color=rainbow(100)) # horrible

library(viridis) # requires installation of viridis package
## Loading required package: viridisLite
pheatmap(cancer.data.m,  color=magma(10)) # quite nice

# heatmap is split by using cutree on the row tree (k=4)
pheatmap(cancer.data.m, cutree_rows = 4)

# comparing this splitup with the 
#k means groups that we made before
# some necessary ground work here - 
#1) making a data frme for "annotation":
#in this case k means groups
temp<-data.frame(kmeans=my.groups$cluster)

# 2) the matrix neeeds row names so that it 
#can be matched with the data frame above. 
row.names(cancer.data.m)<-1:94

# and drawing the heat map
pheatmap(cancer.data.m, cutree_rows = 4, 
         annotation_row=as.factor(temp))

# the idea of using extra rows and 
#columns like this to show other 
# data and how it is "explained" 
#by the clustering is very nice. 
# We typically think of these data as "co-variates"

What is it that we see? Are the same groups as we saw in the plots in a) and b) visible?

SOLUTION

What is it that we see in the plot? The rows correspond to the patients: the tree on the left has ordered them according to similarity. Red means low expression while blue is high, with the original colors. ‘rainbow’ is too messy while ‘magma’ is not to bad.
The really nice thing with this plot in comparison to just the tree which we made above is that we can see that the different clusters really are different in gene expression. In particular, the middle clusters have a much lower expression in gene 2. the “tree” on top is meaningless since we only have two genes. The cuttree_rows option is splitting the rows based on cutree as we did above. Addingthe k mean clusters as a color bar to the left shows the same thing as our table above: trees and k means mostly agree, but diagree on a few of the largest cluster.

–

The real power of heatmaps is to visualize data with many columns and rows at once. To do this, we need more genes than in our cancer example.

The more_patients.txt file has exactly this: rows are genes, columns are patients being exposed to a drug. The first column show gene names, which should not be part of the actual heatmap data - but it should be used as row labels in the matrix so that they get uased as labels in the reulting heatmap. We are told that some of the patients seem to be responding to the drug.

What patients are these and what genes are these? Are most of those gene down-or up-regulated?

If you have time (this is a bit harder): In the file annotation.txt, there is annotation category for each of the genes (gene names in col 1, annotation category in col2). Can you use the annotation categories as an extra columns in the heatmap (like we did for k means in the small heat map above) to make the data even more understandable? Tip: pheatmap annotation_row wants a data frame, it cannot deal with tibbles.

SOLUTION

row.names(more.patients.m)<- more.patients$GeneID
pheatmap((more.patients.m), show_rownames = TRUE)

Again, we have the patients as columns, now ordered after patient similarity (in gene expression), and genes ordered after their similarity, also from gene expression. The tree on the left shows gene expression similarity, the one on top is patient similarity. Here, red is high expression and blue is low.

This illustrates the power of heat maps ??? just from this picture we can identify many interesting feature about the data set:

It is quite clear that there is a group of 5 patients (patients 3, 6, 7, 8, 9) which behave very similarly. These have a set of up-regulated genes (red ??? bottom image), a large set of down-regulated genes (blue, top, and one highly upregulated gene (CDK7), which is very different from the other patients. It is unclear whether the other patients fo m one group or two ??? they seem quite different. It is clear that CDK7 would be a good candidate for a diagnostic marker for these patient groups.

What about adding these extra data as a co-variate (gene classes)?

## challenge 2
annotation<-as.data.frame(read_tsv("gene_annotation.txt")) 
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   GeneID = col_character(),
##   GeneClass = col_character()
## )
# becasue for historical reasons, 
#pheatmap annotation_row likes data frames and not tibbles...
head(annotation)
##   GeneID       GeneClass
## 1  SCN1A     ion channel
## 2   CDK6      cell cycle
## 3  TRPA1     Ion channel
## 4   TPMT Drug metabolism
## 5   E2F1     Cell growth
## 6   TYMP     Cell growth
# we pick only the second row, which is the gene 
#categories, and use the gene IDs as now names
annotation2<-annotation[2]
row.names(annotation2)<-annotation$GeneID
# plot the heatmap 
pheatmap((more.patients.m), annotation_row=annotation2)

This adds a new columns to the left, corresponing to the “gene class” annotation. What we can see is that the genes that are close to one another also share annotation categories, so there appears to be some biology going on here! In particluar, there are big blocks of co-regulated genes from cell cyelce and cell growth categories in the bottom of the heat map.
